Since I'm seeing a lot of "I fell behind" comments, I figured I'd pop in and share where I'm at and how I've been approaching this 30 day yoga journey. 

This is my first time participating in a 30 day yoga journey of any kind, and so I'm doing my best to be gentle with myself and listen to what my body wants and needs, whether that be rest, yoga, a different sort of movement, etc. I used to have a daily practice, but I haven't in years, and so I'm treating this as a way to get myself back into a regular practice. Instead of committing myself to do each day of the journey consecutively, I've been doing each day as I feel ready for it while also being mindful of when my body is open to and up for a challenge. For example, at the beginning, I did three days in a row and then I believe I took three days off. Old me would have shamed myself to high heavens for doing that, but after so long of not moving, I needed the rest so that when I came back for day four, I could actually give it my all. Today, I just finished day 12 and I'm feeling better than ever. I've been doing each day as I feel like it, some days I've even been doing other of Adriene's sequences or other movement such as walking or a body workout with my partner. It's been slow and steady, but I hear that's how you win the race.

So long story short, if you're behind on this yoga journey, know you're not alone and that you'll finish it at the exact time you're meant to.

I misheard the message for today as "where tension flows energy goes," so I found myself trying to make sense of that... and actually coming to some interesting conclusions. They encouraged me to not see difficulty or tension during this practice as weakness but rather, invitation to pursue building strength -- letting tension at my mindful edge change me for the better. I'll carry that into my work today, where I've really been having trouble focusing.

It felt great to really focus on the warmth my efforts were generating and to notice myself getting more confident on the mat during this series. 

Anyway, when it was over, I read the comments, and ofc  "where ATTENTION flows, energy goes" makes way more sense. But I'm going with how I heard it. See ya tomorrow.💀

I've done that so far and for that I am proud. What I'm struggling with now is, why don't I feel much different? I am so tired even though I've been resting for the past 5 days. I have tried perching on a block before, but that's a little scary still hurts. If any of you know, please please help me. I've looked online for help and modifications, but no luck.  I am quite tall and weigh 200 lbs so maybe that's part of it? I'm very flexible though, and strong, so...I just don't know. Lately in these practices I've been feeling like I haven't been getting enough out of them, even though I've been going through all the mindful movements, like navel to spine, lengthen in the neck, press down in all four corners of the feet, all that kind of stuff. Physically, I am finding an increase! But I somehow lost the mental, the deeper fulfilment that is the reason I keep coming back. This practice and the email before helped me to realize and re-find what it means to focus! Even though I felt like I was focusing, I was actually quite distracted. Even discouragement is a distraction. Instead, I can go back to the breath. I think I've been having a lot of thoughts of perfectionism! So instead turning back my focus to what I can control brought more love for me, more power. You're falling out of this balance pose, or you missed a couple of Adriene's repetitions? Okay, all good; keep trying. I'm moving in the way that I can. I also chose to just leave my glasses off for the whole practice. They often come off whenever I'm facing down towards the mat, either because the mat is in the way or they're falling off my face, but then I scramble to put them back on if I'm the slightest unsure as to what Adriene is doing. It required a greater trust, but also a greater focus on her words, and I think it helped bring me to myself rather than on the way Adriene looks in her poses. I'm so grateful for this practice! I struggled with today’s practice. I felt some pain and needed to stop the lunges and slowed things down to my pace. With my runs building my leg muscles, I need to be careful and slow down how I move—I can’t go as fast as Adriene. But I am not her and she is not me. As I watched and practiced the balance moves at the end, I was reminded of how I felt after recovering from a torn Achilles’ a few years back. How impossible it was to stand on my recently healed leg and balance on a foam mat. Now, years later, I’m a different me and am in a different place, the world is different, and all of that is okay. I’m finding the body-mind connection to be the best lessons. It’ll take me years to be at a level where I can move similar to what I see Adriene doing. But that’s okay. One day at a time. Thank you, Adriene for the challenging session today!

I read in the tree of yoga how with practice and time, effort becomes joy. This is my 7th year joining and it has felt like the biggest gift to get a chance to come here every day. Effort has become joy. Time for self-study, growth, challenge, exploration and joy. Even in the asanas that I want to give up on I feel so much satisfaction from pushing through and proving to myself I can be disciplined. The only day I struggled to show up on the mat was our rest day (previous years I've struggled many or most days), and that gave me insight in how I move off the mat, that I've had a habit of procrastinating rest. With time the effort to carve out time to rest will turn into joy too. I'm so grateful I get to move with you, learn about myself and find more joy as I do so. Namaste ❤️
